<article class="read-article">
    <section class="article-main-content daily-devotion scripturizer-content">
        <div class="devotion-date">
            <span class="week-day">Saturday</span>
            <span class="month-day">26</span>
        </div>
        <p><strong>John 14:1</strong> (NLT)</p>
<p>Too often we let our circumstances determine our attitude. If life is going smoothly, then we feel good about ourselves. But when it gets hard, our mood drops. However, we don&rsquo;t have to live this way. Like the apostle Paul, we can learn and practice the secret of being content.</p>
<p>Contentment means accepting things the way they are&mdash;in other words, not wanting anything to be more or different. This requires developing an &ldquo;I can through Christ&rdquo; attitude. It means learning to allow God&rsquo;s power to come into our weakness so we can accept and adapt to changing circumstances. When we respond to life with that kind of thinking, we move beyond living by feelings to living by faith (2 Corinthians 5:7). </p>
<p>Submission and trust are needed for such a lifestyle. First, we must surrender our will to God&rsquo;s: In every situation, we are to yield what we want and then accept whatever He allows. Our desire to control events is replaced by reliance on Him. This option becomes more appealing when we realize that the alternative&mdash;fighting against our circumstances&mdash;brings anxiety and distress. The second step is to trust God to oversee our specific situation. If we believe He is working out His perfect plan for us, then we will experience the joy that comes from trusting Him. Contentment will be ours. </p>
<p>Paul submitted his life to God and trusted Him. He faced insults, rejection, and many difficult trials but was still content. When we surrender control to the Lord and believe He has our best interest at heart, we will experience contentment, too. Who has control in your life? </p>
<p><strong>Bible in One Year: </strong>Nahum 1-3</p>

